<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Penstemon newberryi </i>is a conspicuous perennial or subshrub with showy magenta to reddish flowers and opposite, bluish-green leaves. Its three varieties vary in flower color, shape, and range, but they have similar ecologies: var. <i>newberryi </i>grows in the Cascades and Sierra Nevada, var. <i>berryi </i>in the Klamath Mountains and North Coast ranges, and var. <i>sonomensis </i>in the North Coast ranges. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance is common on montane to subalpine rock outcrops, especially glaciated surfaces throughout the Sierra Nevada and other high mountains of northern California. Stands are most prominent in the early summer when plants are in full bloom. Other herbs, such as <i>Streptanthus tortuosus, </i>are seasonal and annually variable in cover on porous gravelly substrates, while <i>P. newberryi </i>and <i>Juncus parryi </i>persist in rocky crevices and cracks (Sawyer and Keeler-Wolf 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
